{"type":"text","timestamp":1775886444761,"sessionID":"ses_284ebb1d0ffeBv9YVKRFhZV4Mg","part":{"id":"prt_d7b14a6e2001hJVX8dcg00rEBV","messageID":"msg_d7b14860c001zm9PSDZ0fky2mm","sessionID":"ses_284ebb1d0ffeBv9YVKRFhZV4Mg","type":"text","text":"Now I have all the context needed. Let me write the proposal.md file for the CLI build command.","time":{"start":1775886444759,"end":1775886444759}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775886486401,"sessionID":"ses_284ebb1d0ffeBv9YVKRFhZV4Mg","part":{"id":"prt_d7b14a8da001SLfUJOvAb4gsMc","messageID":"msg_d7b14860c001zm9PSDZ0fky2mm","sessionID":"ses_284ebb1d0ffeBv9YVKRFhZV4Mg","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_functions.write:2","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md","content":"# Proposal: CLI Build Command (AR-021)\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement the `build` command for the AgentCube CLI to enable developers to build container images from packaged agent workspaces. The build command is a critical component of the agent lifecycle management workflow, bridging the gap between workspace packaging (`pack`) and deployment/publishing (`publish`).\n\nThe build command SHALL:\n- Build container images from packaged agent workspaces using Docker\n- Support both local Docker builds and cloud-based builds\n- Handle version incrementation automatically during the build process\n- Provide proxy configuration for dependency resolution in restricted network environments\n- Integrate seamlessly with the existing `pack` and `publish` commands\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n\n1. **CLI Command Implementation**\n   - Add `build` subcommand to the Typer CLI application\n   - Command options:\n     - `workspace` (`-f`, `--workspace`): Path to agent workspace directory (default: \".\")\n     - `proxy` (`-p`, `--proxy`): Custom proxy URL for dependency resolution\n     - `cloud_provider` (`--cloud-provider`): Cloud provider name (e.g., huawei)\n     - `output` (`--output`): Output path for build artifacts\n     - `verbose` (`--verbose`): Enable detailed logging\n\n2. **BuildRuntime Implementation**\n   - `BuildRuntime` class in `agentcube/runtime/build_runtime.py`\n   - Core methods:\n     - `build(workspace_path, **options)`: Main build orchestration\n     - `_validate_build_prerequisites()`: Verify Docker availability and workspace state\n     - `_build_local()`: Execute local Docker builds\n     - `_build_cloud()`: Execute cloud-based builds\n     - `_increment_version()`: Automatic version bumping (patch level)\n     - `_update_build_metadata()`: Persist build results to metadata\n\n3. **Docker Integration**\n   - Leverage existing `DockerService` for image building\n   - Support build arguments (e.g., proxy settings)\n   - Tag images with version-derived tags\n   - Return build metadata (image_name, image_id, image_size, build_time)\n\n4. **Version Management**\n   - Automatic version increment on successful build:\n     - Semantic versioning: patch bump for `X.Y.Z` ŌåÆ `X.Y.Z+1`\n     - Fallback: append `.1` for non-semver versions\n     - Fallback: `{version}-1` for edge cases\n   - Version rollback on build failure to maintain consistency\n\n5. **Error Handling**\n   - Docker unavailability detection with clear error messaging\n   - Build failure handling with verbose traceback support\n   - Integration with `_handle_error()` for consistent CLI error patterns\n\n### Out of Scope\n\n1. **Image Publishing**: Handled by the `publish` command\n2. **Registry Authentication**: Managed during `publish` phase\n3. **Multi-platform Builds**: Single-platform builds only (current iteration)\n4. **Build Caching Optimization**: Standard Docker caching behavior\n5. **Custom Build Drivers**: Only Docker daemon-based builds\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Affected Components\n\n| Component | Impact Level | Description |\n|-----------|--------------|-------------|\n| `agentcube/cli/main.py` | High | New `build` command registration and option handling |\n| `agentcube/runtime/build_runtime.py` | High | New runtime class implementation |\n| `agentcube/runtime/__init__.py` | Medium | Export `BuildRuntime` class |\n| `agentcube/__init__.py` | Low | Add `BuildRuntime` to exports (consistent with other runtimes) |\n| `agentcube/services/docker_service.py` | Low | Reuse existing `build_image()` method |\n| `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py` | Low | Metadata read/write for version tracking |\n\n### Dependencies\n\n**Required:**\n- `pack` command must be executed before `build` (validated via metadata)\n- `DockerService` must be functional for local builds\n- `AgentMetadata` model for version and configuration storage\n\n**Dependent:**\n- `publish` command depends on successful `build` output\n- Status tracking depends on build metadata\n\n### Risk Assessment\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|--------|------------|\n| Docker daemon unavailable | Medium | High | Clear error message; validate prerequisites early |\n| Version increment conflicts | Low | Medium | Atomic metadata updates; rollback on failure |\n| Cloud provider API failures | Low | High | Fallback to local build; clear error reporting |\n| Large workspace build timeouts | Medium | Medium | Document timeout limits; support for build args |\n\n### Performance Considerations\n\n- Build times scale with workspace size and dependency complexity\n- Docker image layer caching reduces subsequent build times\n- Version increment operations are lightweight (file I/O only)\n- Cloud builds may have variable latency based on provider\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Integrated Pack+Build Command\n\n**Approach:** Combine `pack` and `build` into a single `prepare` command.\n\n**Rejected:** Keeps concerns separatedŌĆöpacking prepares the workspace structure while building creates the container image. Users may want to pack without building (e.g., to review Dockerfile), and the separation enables better error isolation.\n\n### Alternative 2: External Build Tool Integration\n\n**Approach:** Delegate builds to external tools like `kaniko`, `buildah`, or cloud-native buildpacks.\n\n**Rejected:** Adds external dependencies and complexity. The Docker SDK provides sufficient functionality for the initial release. Future iterations may add pluggable build backends.\n\n### Alternative 3: Manual Version Management\n\n**Approach:** Require users to manually update version before each build.\n\n**Rejected:** Error-prone and friction-heavy. Automatic version increment ensures consistent versioning while preserving the ability to override via `agent_metadata.yaml`.\n\n### Alternative 4: Build Cache Externalization\n\n**Approach:** Support external build cache backends (S3, registry).\n\n**Rejected:** Increases complexity without clear benefit for initial use cases. Can be added later if build performance becomes a bottleneck.\n\n### Alternative 5: Buildkit-Only Builds\n\n**Approach:** Require BuildKit for all builds to enable advanced features.\n\n**Rejected:** Not all environments have BuildKit enabled. Standard Docker builds provide broader compatibility.\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n### Build Mode Resolution\n\n1. Read `build_mode` from metadata (default: \"local\")\n2. Local builds use `DockerService.build_image()`\n3. Cloud builds delegate to provider-specific implementations\n\n### Version Increment Logic\n\n```python\n# Pseudo-code for version increment\ndef increment_version(current_version: str) -> str:\n    if current_version matches semver(X.Y.Z):\n        return bump_patch(X.Y.Z)\n    elif current_version contains dots:\n        return append_dot_increment(current_version)\n    else:\n        return f\"{current_version}-1\"\n```\n\n### Error Handling Pattern\n\nAll build errors SHALL propagate through `_handle_error()`:\n- Non-verbose: Print concise error message in red\n- Verbose: Print full traceback\n- Exit code: 1 on any build failure\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n1. `agentcube build` successfully creates Docker images from packaged workspaces\n2. Version is automatically incremented on successful builds\n3. Version is rolled back on build failures\n4. Docker unavailability produces clear error messages\n5. Build metadata is persisted to `agent_metadata.yaml`\n6. Command integrates with existing CLI error handling patterns\n7. Unit tests cover happy path and error scenarios\n"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775886486390,"end":1775886486398}}}}
